personLists.name: Billionaires
personLists.bio: Zuckerberg made the first ever Under 30 list in 2012, eight years after he started Facebook in his Harvard dorm room. At the time, his social network had amassed 845 million users and was readying for its $100 billion May 2012 IPO. Now called Meta, the company has 3.6 billion users across its Facebook, Instagram and WhatsApp as its market cap hovers around $1 trillion. But amid declining interest from young users and a tarnished brand, Zuckerberg is shifting his focus to virtual reality and a still unproven idea for a metaverse.

personLists.name: Billionaires
personLists.bio: Zhang founded ByteDance in 2012 in a four-bedroom Beijing apartment and launched news-aggregation app Toutiao months later. He appeared on the Forbes Under 30 list in 2013 at age 29. Today he and his company are best known for the insanely app TikTok. It has more than 1 billion users worldwide, but its future will be in the hands of someone other than Zhang, who stepped down as ByteDance's chairman in November as the Chinese government exerts more pressure on high-profile CEOs.

personLists.bio: When he joined the 2021 Under 30 ranks, his FTX cryptocurrency exchange had just raised $40 million at a $1.2 billion valuation. Two huge fundraising rounds later -- at an $18 billion valuation in July and a $25 billion valuation in October -- Bankman-Fried is now the richest under-30 on the planet, worth $26.5 billion.
